While almost every [[weighing scale]] uses the same basic principle (the gravitational force exerted by an object divided by the area the force is applied on), industrial weighing scales are designed to do a lot more. They handle heavier loads, often in different conditions, both environmental and physical.

The terminology applied to different industrial weighing systems is widely ranged, with some terms adapted specifically for them, which are included in this glossary.  Modern scales are electronic, and often computer-networked; consequently, the field has imported a fair amount of terminology from [[electrical engineering]] and [[Computer networking|computerized data transfer]].

{{Compact ToC|k=|q=|x=|y=}}

==A==
{{glossary}}
{{term|accumulator}}
{{defn|content=A device that receives, totals and stores weighing data, designed as a circuit or register linked to a computer.}}

{{term|accuracy}}
{{defn|content=The precision of 1) measurements made by a weighing system, and 2) the statement of physical characteristics. It is expressed in terms of error, as a percentage of: a) the specified value (e.g., 10 volts ± 1%), b) a range (e.g., 2% of full scale), or c) as parts (e.g., 100 parts per million).}}

{{term|analog-to-digital|content={{vanchor|analog-to-digital (A/D)|analog to digital|Analog-to-Digital|AD|A/D}} }}
{{term|analog-to-digital converter |content={{vanchor|analog-to-digital converter (ADC)|analog to digital converter|Analog-to-Digital Converter|A/D/C|ADC}} |multi=y}}
{{defn|content=The conversion of analog (continuously varying) voltage levels to digital (binary-numbered) values. E.g., an analog-to-digital converter can translate load cell output that is fed into it, into a continuous stream of digitized information to be sent to a digital indicator.}}

{{term|ambient conditions}}
{{defn|content=Humidity, pressure, temperature and other conditions present in the medium surrounding a load cell.}}

{{term|ampere}}
{{defn|content={{main|Ampere}}
Unit of electric current intensity, measured as 6.24 x 10<sup>18</sup> electrons passing a point in one second. Abbreviated '''amp'''.}}

{{term|analog}}
{{defn|content=Information represented by continuous values instead of discrete steps; point for point or value for value data that corresponds to an otherwise unrelated quantity.}}

{{term|angular load, concentric |content=angular load, concentric{{anchor|concentric angular load}} }}
{{defn|content=Load applied concentric with (common center), and at an angle to, the primary axis at the point of application.}}

{{term|angular load, eccentric |content=angular load, eccentric{{anchor|eccentric angular load}} }}
{{defn|content=Load applied eccentric with (off center), and at an angle to, the primary axis at the point of application.}}

{{term|aperture}}
{{defn|content=Percentage range of full scale capacity, over which digital weight indicator functions AZM (Automatic Zero Maintenance) and PAZ (Push-button Auto Zero) will operate, according to Handbook 44.}}

{{term|approved}}
{{defn|content=System or equipment that is acceptable to the authority with [[jurisdiction]] over the area in which it will be used.}}

{{term|American Standard Code for Information Interchange |content={{vanchor|American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII)|American Standard Code for Information Interchange|ASCII}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|American Standard Code for Information Interchange}}
Seven-bit plus parity code established by the [[American National Standards Institute]] (ANSI) to achieve compatibility between data services. Pronounced "askee".}}

{{term|associated apparatus}}
{{defn|content=Devices relied upon to maintain intrinsic safety, designed with circuits that may not be intrinsically safe themselves, but may affect the energy in intrinsically safe circuits.}}

{{term|asynchronous transmission}}
{{defn|content=Data transmission where time intervals between transmitted characters may be of unequal length. Controlled by start bits at the beginning and stop bits at the end of each character.}}

{{term|authority having jurisdiction}}
{{defn|content=May be a federal, state, local or other regional institution, department or individual that has jurisdiction where public safety is primary. E.g., fire chief, fire marshal, chief of fire protection bureau.}}

{{term|auto-ignition temperature |content={{vanchor|auto-ignition temperature (AIT)|autoignition temperature|AIT}} }}
{{defn|content=''(Also '''ignition temperature''');'' lowest temperature that will cause a substance to initiate or induce self-sustained combustion independently of heating or heated equipment.}}

{{term|automatic zero maintenance |content={{vanchor|automatic zero maintenance (AZM)|automatic-zero maintenance|AZM|autozero maintenance|auto-zero maintenance|auto zero maintenance|auto-zero|autozero|auto zero}} }}
{{defn|content=Electronic method of providing "true zero" on a digital scale, at all times. Compensates for conditions like indicator or load cell drift or debris on a scale platform by electronically tracking out minor variations around zero.}}

{{term|automatic shut-off |content=automatic shut-off{{anchor|automatic shutoff|automatic shut off|auto shut-off|auto shutoff|auto shut off||auto-shut-off|auto-shutoff}} }}
{{defn|content=Function that turns off a weighing device or unit after a pre-set duration, if no active weighing occurs during that time.}}

{{term|average piece weight |content={{vanchor|average piece weight (APW)|average piece-weight|average pieceweight|APVW}} }}
{{defn|content=Measurement of total weight divided by number of samples weighed in one batch on a counting scale. Used to determine the count of pieces during normal operation, where total weight of large batches is divided by average piece weight.}}

{{term|axial load}}
{{defn|content=Load applied along a line concentric with the primary axis at the point of application.}}
{{glossary end}}

==B==
{{glossary}}
{{term|baud}}
{{defn|content=A unit of communications processing speed in digital data communications systems, measured as the number of discrete conditions of signal events per second. If each signal event represents only one bit condition, baud rate equals bits per second (BPS).}}

{{term|beam}}
{{defn|content=A device used as an indicator for a lever scale.}}

{{term|bezel}}
{{defn|content=A holder that is designed to receive and position the edges of a lens, meter, window or display.}}

{{term|bi-directional |content=bi-direction{{anchor|bidirection|bidi|bi-di|BiDi}} }}
{{defn|content=Information flow in either direction on a wire between pieces of equipment that are equipped for both receiving and transmitting data. May be abbreviated '''bi-di''' or '''BiDi'''.}}

{{term|binary-coded decimal |content={{vanchor|binary-coded decimal (BCD)|binary coded decimal|BCD}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Binary-coded decimal}}
A data coding system in which the decimal numbers 0 through 9 are represented by four binary bits. E.g., the binary coded decimal equivalent of the number 187 is 0001 1000 0111.}}

{{term|bit}}
{{defn|content={{main|bit}}
The smallest unit of information in a binary system, consisting of a <code>0</code> or a <code>1</code>. Abbreviated from "binary digit".}}

{{term|blackout}}
{{defn|content=A sudden loss of AC line power which normally occurs due to an overload or other power failure.}}

{{term|Board of Governors}}
{{defn|content=The body of officials from the [[National Conference on Weights and Measures]] that sets [[National Type Evaluation Program]] (NTEP) policy and has final say in disputes.}}

{{term|bridge circuit}}
{{defn|content=A network of four "leg" components connected in such a way that the input signal may be applied across two branches in parallel, and the output signal taken between two points, one on each side of the parallel branches. The output voltage is zero when the output points are at the same potential, which occurs at some ratio of the resultant four arms of the circuit, and the bridge is said to be balanced or set to null at that point.}}

{{term|brownout}}
{{defn|content=A power company's deliberate lowering of line voltage in order to reduce load demands.}}
{{glossary end}}

==C==
{{glossary}}
{{term|calibration}}
{{defn|content={{main|Calibration}}
A comparison of the outputs of load cells against standard test loads, to check for accuracy and any errors in measurement.}}

{{term|calibration curve}}
{{defn|content={{main|Calibration curve}}
A record (graph) of the comparison of load cell outputs against standard test loads.}}

{{term|calibration error}}
{{defn|content=Any difference between what the weighing equipment reads on the display, and the item's true mass as measured by a calibrated instrument.}}

{{term|cantilever beam}}
{{defn|content=A beam-type load cell with strain gauges or load-sensing elements mounted on the inside perimeter of a machined-out center.}}

{{term|capacitance}}
{{defn|content={{main|Capacitance}}
The ability of a component or material to store an electrostatic charge; measured in farads. Because the farad is a very large quantity, capacitance in electronic applications is usually expressed in millionths of a farad (microfarads) or millionths of a millionth of a farad (pico farads).}}

{{term|capacity}}
{{defn|content=The amount of weight that a scale or weighing device can accurately weigh.}}

{{term|central processing unit |content={{vanchor|central processing unit (CPU)|central-processing unit|CPU}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Central processing unit}}
A computer module or chip that controls processing operations for the device by fetching, decoding and executing instructions.}}

{{term|[[challan]]}}
{{defn|content=A payment or delivery receipt.}}

{{term|check rods}}
{{defn|content=Rods that are installed on a vessel or other weighing system component to prevent gross tipping or extended travel. They do not interfere with normal travel or expansion.}}

{{term|check weigher |content=check weigher{{anchor|checkweigher|check-weigher}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Check weigher}}
A scale used to verify predetermined weight within prescribed limits.}}

{{term|class III scales}}
{{defn|content=Classes of scales used in commercial weighing that are not otherwise specified. These include grain test scales, retail precious metals and semiprecious gem weighing, animal scales, postal scales, and scales used to determine laundry charges.}}

{{term|class IIIL scales}}
{{defn|content=Vehicle, axle-load, livestock, railway track scales, crane and hopper (other than grain hopper) scales.}}

{{term|complementary metal oxide semiconductor |content={{vanchor|complementary metal oxide semiconductor (CMOS)|complementary-metal oxide semiconductor|CMOS}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|CMOS}}
Chip technology characterized by a low power requirement and high noise immunity, but susceptible to damage by [[electrostatic discharge]] (ESD).}}

{{term|combined error |content={{vanchor|combined error (non-linearity and hysteresis)}} }}
{{defn|content=The maximum deviation from the straight line drawn between the original no-load and rated load outputs (measured on both increasing and decreasing loads), and expressed as a percentage of the rated output.}}

{{term|compensation}}
{{defn|content=Use of supplementary equipment, materials or processes in order to minimize any known sources of error.}}

{{term|compression |content={{vanchor|compression (physical)|compression (physics)}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Compression (physics)}}
A force applied to a strain gauge that decreases gauge resistance by causing the gauge wires to compress and their cross-sectional area to increase. Not to be confused with [[data compression]].}}

{{term|concentrated load capacity |content={{vanchor|concentrated load capacity (CLC)|CLC}} }}
{{defn|content=Maximum load that can be placed anywhere on the platform of a vehicle, axle-load or livestock scale using the prescribed test pattern (an area at least 4 feet long and as wide as the scale platform), as designated by the manufacturer.}}

{{term|conformally coated}}
{{defn|content=Load cells that have a protective coating applied over the strain gauges, terminal strip, etc., within the gauged cavity, which may also be covered with side plates to protect against physical damage. These cells are designed for use in normal indoor applications and should not be used in wet or washdown applications.}}

{{term|continuous mode |content=continuous mode{{anchor|continuous-mode}} }}
{{defn|content=Transmission of serial output data in which information is transmitted automatically following each indicator display update. It is usually used to interface indicators to remote devices that require constant data updating, like computers and score boards.}}

{{term|control drawing}}
{{defn|content=A drawing or document which details the allowed interconnections between the intrinsically safe or associated apparatus and is provided by the manufacturer of the equipment.}}

{{term|cornerload |content=cornerload{{anchor|corner-load|corner load}}}}
{{defn|content=The ability of an instrument to deliver the same weight reading for an object placed on the corners of the weighing pan.}}

{{term|cornerload error}}
{{defn|content=Variations in the weight of an object that is moved to corner positions on the weighing pan.}}

{{term|count}}
{{defn|content=The smallest increment of weight that is displayed by the instrument.}}

{{term|creep}}
{{defn|content=Change in load cell output that occurs with time, while under load, and with all environmental conditions and other variables remaining constant. It is usually measured with rated load applied and expressed as a percent of rated output over a specific duration.}}

{{term|creep recovery}}
{{defn|content=The change in no-load output occurring with time, after removal of a load which has been applied for a specific period of time. It is usually measured over a specified time period that immediately follows the removal of rated load, and is expressed as a percent of rated output.}}

{{term|current}}
{{defn|content={{main|Electric current}}
Flow of electrons past a point within a specified period of time, which is measured in amperes.}}

{{term|current loop}}
{{defn|content={{main|Current loop}}
A current-based method of serial communications between digital devices where a logic "high" is represented by current flowing in the loop, and a logic "low" is represented by a lack of current flowing in the loop.}}
{{glossary end}}

==D==
{{glossary}}
{{term|D |content={{vanchor|D (division)|d (division)|d}} }}
{{defn|content=Value of the smallest increment that is indicated (displayed) by a scale's {{glossary link internal|divisions}}.}}

{{term|dash pot}}
{{defn|content=A dampening device that is used to reduce scale oscillations.}}

{{term|dead load |content=dead load{{anchor|deadload|dead-load}} }}
{{defn|content=The fixed force of load-supporting structures of the scale (like the weigh bridge or platform), the value of which needs to be permanently balanced or cancelled out in the weight or measuring system.}}

{{term|decimal point}}
{{defn|content={{main|Decimal mark}}
Determines the location of the decimal point or number of dummy zeros for the graduation size. E.g., 8888.88 would have two places to the right of the decimal point, 888880 would have one dummy zero.}}

{{term|deflection}}
{{defn|content=Change in length along the primary axis of the load cell between no-load and rated load conditions.}}

{{term|demand mode}}
{{defn|content=Transmission of serial output data, which needs a manual "Print" command to initiate the output data. It is usually used to interface indicators to printers.}}

{{term|numerical digit}}
{{defn|content={{main|Numerical digit}}
The smallest increment of weight that the indicator resolves.}}

{{term|digital}}
{{defn|content={{main|Digital data}}
A system of signal representation that employs discrete values instead of continuously variable (analog) values.}}

{{term|digital averaging}}
{{defn|content=A digital indicator's ability to smooth bouncy or erratic readings before sending the signal to the display, by taking several readings and averaging them together. Increasing the digital averaging slows the indicator's update rate.}}

{{term|digital filtering}}
{{defn|content=Used to stabilize the readout of the indicator. More digital filtering applied leads to a more accurate display reading, but a longer settling time is required.}}

{{term|display divisions}}
{{defn|content=Selects the minimum division size for the displayed weight of primary units, and determines if the count by will be 1, 2, or 5.}}

{{term|divisions |content=divisions{{anchor|division}} }}
{{defn|content=Determines the amount of increments in weight that a scale offers.}}

{{term|dormant scale}}
{{defn|content=A built-in weighing scale with a self-contained understructure.}}

{{term|dot matrix |content=dot matrix{{anchor|dotmatrix|dot-matrix}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Dot matrix}}
A method of printing where a rectangular array (matrix) of spaces is filled in to form alphanumeric and punctuation characters.}}

{{term|dribble}}
{{defn|content=The weight value over which material is slowly handled to provide a more accurate cutoff in filling operations.}}

{{term|drift}}
{{defn|content=A continuously upward or downward change in the number displayed on the digital readout, which could occur due to temperature, static electricity or radio frequency interference (RFI).}}

{{term|dropout |content=dropout{{anchor|drop-out|drop out}} }}
{{defn|content=A temporary loss of electrical power, which is normally caused by break-before-make switching strategies used in utility and maintenance switching functions.}}

{{term|dual in-line package |content={{vanchor|dual in-line package (DIP)|dual inline package|DIP}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Dual in-line package}}
An integrated circuit contained within a standard housing characterized by its low profile, rectangular body, and symmetrical placement of leads along two opposing sides the device.}}
{{glossary end}}

