{{term|eccentric load}}
{{defn|content=Any load applied parallel to, but not concentric with, the primary axis.}}

{{term|electrical noise}}
{{defn|content=Extraneous undesirable currents or voltages that interfere with desirable electrical quantities. Some causes are distant lightning, radio transmitters, welding equipment, electrical switching equipment, poor brush contact on motors, and other electronic devices utilizing switching power supplies.}}

{{term|electrically erasable programmable read-only memory |content={{vanchor|electrically erasable programmable read-only memory (EEPROM)|electrically erasable programmable read only memory|electrically erasable programmable readonly memory|EEPROM|EEPROMs}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|EEPROM}}
A component of data storage where data can be repeatedly read out, stored data can be erased by an electrical signal and new data can then be programmed into the component.}}

{{term|electromagnetic interference |content={{vanchor|electromagnetic interference (EMI)|EMI|electro-magnetic interference}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Electromagnetic interference}}
Interference caused by electrical fields due to capacitive coupling, or magnetic fields due to mutual inductance of electromagnetic fields (radio waves).}}

{{term|electron}}
{{defn|content={{main|Electron}}
A negatively charged subatomic particle that orbits the nucleus of an atom. The flow of electrons determines electric current.}}

{{term|electrostatic charge |content=electrostatic charge{{anchor|electro-static charge}} }}
{{defn|content=An electric charge on the surface of an insulated object.}}

{{term|electrostatic discharge |content={{vanchor|electrostatic discharge (ESD)|ESD|electro-static discharge}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Electrostatic discharge}}
A rapid discharge of an electrostatic potential, which can cause damage to integrated circuits.}}

{{term|environmentally protected}}
{{defn|content=Load cells that feature a strain gauge cavity filled with a potting compound to protect them from normal environmental factors in indoor or outdoor applications. The cavity opening is also generally protected against physical damage, with loose-fitting side plates or molded plastic. These cells should not be submersed or washed down.}}

{{term|erasable programmable read-only memory |content={{vanchor|erasable programmable read-only memory (EPROM)|EPROM|erasable programmable readonly memory|erasable programmable read only memory}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|EPROM}}
A component of data storage where data can be repeatedly read out, stored data can be erased by applying ultraviolet light and new data can then be programmed into the component.}}

{{term|error}}
{{defn|content=The algebraic difference between the indicated and true value of the load being measured.}}

{{term|excitation}}
{{defn|content=The voltage or current applied to the load cell's input terminals.}}

{{term|excitation trim}}
{{defn|content=Method of adjusting the excitation voltage to each individual load cell in order to match load cell outputs in a multicell system. Adjustment is made by changing the setting of a variable resistor in series with the excitation input.}}

{{term|explosion-proof enclosure |content=explosion-proof enclosure{{anchor|explosion proof enclosure}} }}
{{defn|content=An enclosure that is designed to withstand specified gas or vapor explosions which may occur within it, and to prevent the ignition of the gas surrounding the enclosure. It must also operate at an external temperature which makes it incapable of igniting its surrounding atmosphere.}}
{{glossary end}}

