==H==
{{glossary}}
{{term|half duplex |content=half duplex{{anchor|half-duplex}} }}
{{defn|content=Data transmission in both directions, but not simultaneously. See {{glossary link internal|full duplex}}.}}

{{term|Handbook 44 |content=''Handbook 44''}}
{{defn|content=(Complete title: ''Specifications, Tolerances, and Other Technical Requirements for Weighing and Measuring Devices''); a comprehensive set of requirements for weighing and measuring devices that are used in commerce and law enforcement activities; not a federal law, but developed and updated annually by the [[National Conference on Weights and Measures]]. Often abbreviated ''H-44''.}}

{{term|handshaking}}
{{defn|content={{main|Handshaking}}
Exchange of predetermined signals between two devices, for the purpose of control and data exchange.}}

{{term|Hazardous location}}
{{defn|content=''Also '''hazardous-classified location''' or '''classified-hazardous location'''.'' A location where the presence of flammable gases or vapors, flammable liquids, combustible dust or easily ignitable fibers or flyings may cause fire or explosion hazards.}}

{{term|hermetically sealed}}
{{defn|content=Load cells with a metallic protective cover that welded or soldered in place to protect the strain gauge cavity. Some cells have additional protection like glass-to-metal seals at the cable entry. These load cells provide the best possible protection in harsh chemical or washdown environments.}}

{{term|high-pass filter |content=high-pass filter{{anchor|highpass filter|high pass filter}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|High-pass filter}}
A filter passing frequency that accepts components above a designated frequency and rejects components below that frequency.}}

{{term|hysteresis}}
{{defn|content={{main|Hysteresis}}
The maximum difference between load cell output readings for the same applied load. One reading is obtained by increasing the load from zero, and the other by decreasing the load from rated load. To minimize creep, measurements should be taken as swiftly as possible.}}

{{term|hysteresis error}}
{{defn|content=Different readings obtained for the same object.}}
{{glossary end}}

