{{term|raintight |content=raintight{{anchor|rain-tight|rain tight}} }}
{{defn|content=An enclosure that is constructed or protected in a way such that exposure to a beating rain will not result in the entrance of water under specified test conditions.}}

{{term|random-access memory |content={{vanchor|random-access memory (RAM) |random access memory|RAM}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Random-access memory}}
A data storage device that can be accessed in any order, known as a read/write memory since information can be written into it and then read out by the microprocessor when needed. Contents are lost when the system is powered down.}}

{{term|readability}}
{{defn|content={{main|Readability}}
Smallest division increments display.{{clarify|date=September 2015|reason=That's meaningless word-salad.}}}}

{{term|reactance}}
{{defn|content=The opposition offered to the flow of alternating current by pure capacitance, pure inductance, or a combination of the two. Measured in ohms.}}

{{term|read-only memory |content={{vanchor|read-only memory (ROM)|read only memory|ROM}} }}
{{defn|content={{main|Read-only memory}}
A memory unit in which information or instructions are permanently stored for use by the machine, or for reference by the user. Stored data is read out non-destructively and no information can subsequently be written into the memory.}}

{{term|reference standard}}
{{defn|content=A force-measuring device whose characteristics are precisely known relative to a primary standard.}}

{{term|remote sensing}}
{{defn|content=A method of regulating the excitation voltage to the load cells. Some indicators compensate for voltage drops that occur between the indicator and load cells by increasing the indicator excitation output voltage, others by amplifying the load cell return signal.}}

{{term|repeatability}}
{{defn|content=The maximum difference between load cell output readings for repeated loadings under identical conditions (loading and environmental); the ability of an instrument, system, or method to give identical performance or results in successive instances.}}

{{term|resistance}}
{{defn|content=Opposition to the current-flow that is offered by a purely resistive component; simple opposition to current flow. Measured in ohms. See also {{glossary link internal|reactance}}; not to be confused with {{glossary link internal|resistivity}}.}}

{{term|resistivity}}
{{defn|content={{main|Electrical resistivity and conductivity}}
The electrical resistance offered by a unit cube of material to the flow of direct current (DC) between opposite faces of the cube. Measured in ohm-centimeters. Not to be confused with {{glossary link internal|resistance}}.}}

{{term|resolution}}
{{defn|content=The smallest change in mechanical input that produces a detectable change in the output signal.}}

{{term|RS-232}}
{{defn|content={{main|RS-232}}
A voltage-based serial method of data communication used to transfer data between digital devices. Two wires carry data; one wire is signal ground, and several control wires may be used for handshaking. A logic "high" is from -3 to -25 volts and a logic "low" is from +3 to +25 volts. Transmission distance should be restricted to 50 feet.}}

{{term|RS-422}}
{{defn|content={{main|RS-422}}
A communication method that provides for data transmission using balanced or differential signaling, with unidirectional/non-eversible, terminated or non-terminated transmission lines, point to point, or multi-drop. In contrast to RS-485 (which is multi-point instead of multi-drop) RS-422 does not allow multiple drivers but only multiple receivers.}}

{{term|RS-485}}
{{defn|content={{main|RS-485}}
A data communication method that can be effectively used in electrically noisy environments as well as over long distances. Multiple receivers may be connected in a linear, multi-drop configuration, which make these networks useful in industrial environments and similar applications.}}
{{glossary end}}

