The '''''Oswego-Guardian''–''Texanita'' collision''' was a maritime accident between two supertankers near [[Stilbaai]], South Africa on 21 August 1972.<ref name="Inerting">{{cite paper|url=http://www.c4tx.org/ctx/pub/igs.pdf|title=The Strange History of Tank Inerting|author=Jack Devanney|publisher=Center for Tankship Excellence|date=2010-04-21}}</ref>  The ''Texanita'' exploded and sank with the loss of 47 men, while a further life was lost on the ''Oswego Guardian''.  The accident was a catalyst for change to marine traffic separation procedures as well as oil tanker [[inert gas|inerting]].

==Accident==
{{Location map+|Western Cape|caption=Western Cape, South Africa|width=200|relief=1|places=
{{Location map~|Western Cape|lon_dir=E|lat_dir=S|lat_deg=34.8|lat_min=0|lat_sec=0|lon_deg=21.4|lon_min=0|lon_sec=0|label=Collision|position=right}}
{{Location map~|Western Cape|lon_dir=E|lat_dir=S|lat_deg=34|lat_min=50|lat_sec=0|lon_deg=20|lon_min=0|lon_sec=9|label=Cape Agulhas|position=top}}
{{Location map~|Western Cape|lon_dir=E|lat_dir=S|lat_deg=34|lat_min=22|lat_sec=6|lon_deg=21|lon_min=24|lon_sec=40|label=Stilbaai|position=top}}
}}
The ''Oswego-Guardian'' was rounding the southern tip of Africa, fully loaded with crude oil from the Middle East, while the ''Texanita'' was in ballast, and headed in the opposite direction from [[Trinidad]] to [[Ras Tanura]]. Both ships were approximately 100,000 tons deadweight and registered in [[Liberia]]. The ships collided in dense fog off [[Stilbaai]], near [[Cape Agulhas]].  The oil vapours in the ''Texanita'''s two empty tanks ignited, creating a massive explosion that tore the ship apart, causing it to sink in four minutes with the loss of 47 of its 50 crew;<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d0AyAQAAIAAJ|title=Naval Review|publisher=United States Naval Institute|year=1973}}</ref> the explosion was heard {{convert|63|mi|km}} away, inland from the coast.

A [[United Nations resolution]]<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[International Maritime Organization]]|url=http://www.imo.org/about/conventions/listofconventions/pages/international-convention-for-the-safety-of-life-at-sea-(solas),-1974.aspx|title=International Convention for the Safety of Life at Sea (SOLAS)|year=1974}}</ref> that would have made the use of [[inert gas]] safety systems mandatory for oil tankers, was still in draft in 1972.  Experts believe that were the ''Texanita'' inerted, her fate might have been less tragic, possibly like that of the [[Venpet-Venoil collision|''Venoil'']].<ref name="Inerting"/>

The subsequent investigation determined that the masters of both ships failed to maintain an adequate lookout or to plot the course of the opposite ship; both ships also failed to reduce speed, despite observing one another on radar.  At the time, the accident was the biggest tanker collision on record.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Economist]]|year=1972|volume= 244|page=67}}</ref>  One of the ''Texanita'''s lifeboats was found at [[Bunbury, Western Australia]] two years later.{{cn|date=July 2015}}

==Aftermath==
The accident contributed to an overhaul of the international maritime [[Traffic Separation Scheme|traffic separation system]] that was in force at the time.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hWFWAAAAMAAJ|title=|journal=Navigation|volume= 27-28|page=260|publisher=Institute of Navigation|year=1980}}</ref>

